# [CBOR](../wg/cbor.html)

## Summary
The CBOR working group meeting at IETF 125 focused primarily on the status and technical details of [draft-ietf-cbor-serialization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-serialization/). The discussion centered on the inclusion of test vectors and examples within the draft, the handling of floating-point NaNs, and the coordination of the working group's workflow regarding "parked" documents. The group decided to proceed with adding a curated set of examples to the serialization draft while simultaneously resuming work on [draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals/) and [draft-ietf-cbor-packed](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-packed/).

## Key Discussion Points

### Serialization Draft Status
Lawrence Lundblade presented the status of [draft-ietf-cbor-serialization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-serialization/) based on [Serialization draft status and discussion](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-cbor-serialization-draft-status-and-discussion-00).

*   **Changes in Draft-04:**
    *   Renamed "ordinary serialization" to "preferred plus."
    *   Removed Appendix C (deterministic serialization for common tags).
    *   Expanded the introduction to provide better rationale.
    *   Renamed control operators (notably, `.DET` was already taken).
*   **Open Issues:**
    *   The group is considering moving Appendix B (Rationale) to the main body (requested by Rohan Mahy).
    *   Proposal to move the NaN appendix to a separate document.
    *   Integration of a Pull Request (PR) from Carsten Bormann regarding Section 1 text.

### Test Vectors and Examples
A significant portion of the session was dedicated to the proposal for including test vectors/examples in [draft-ietf-cbor-serialization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-serialization/).

*   **Proposal:** Lawrence Lundblade proposed testing three types of serialization: General, Preferred Plus, and Deterministic. The focus is strictly on serialization valid items rather than fuzzing or well-formedness testing.
*   **Technical Details:**
    *   Examples would use Extended Diagnostic Notation (EDN).
    *   The schema for examples includes a description, EDN representation, and allowed serializations for each of the three modes.
    *   Specific examples discussed included integer 0, maps with varying key orders (where order is not significant in the data model), and NaN payloads.
*   **Decoder Behavior:**
    *   Discussion on how "checking" vs. "non-checking" decoders handle non-preferred serializations.
    *   For NaN payloads, Lawrence Lundblade noted that a "Preferred Plus" non-checking decoder might error out, convert to a quiet NaN, or return the payload depending on implementation, as long as it correctly decodes all valid Preferred Plus inputs.
*   **Documentation Strategy:**
    *   Barry Leiba suggested putting extensive test vectors in a separate informational document.
    *   Carsten Bormann and Lawrence Lundblade argued that examples are essential within the main draft to provide "framing" and clarity for the normative text.
    *   Hank Birkholz suggested that while large sets of vectors belong in a GitHub repository, a curated set of representative examples should remain in the RFC.

### Workflow and Document Priorities
The chairs and the working group discussed how to progress the current workload.

*   **Unparking Documents:** The group had previously "parked" [draft-ietf-cbor-packed](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-packed/) and [draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals/) to focus on serialization.
*   **Dependencies:** Rohan Mahy and Hank Birkholz noted that other specifications (such as SDCOT) have normative dependencies on [draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals/).
*   **Path Forward:** There was general agreement to resume work on EDN and Packed CBOR in parallel with the finalization of the serialization draft.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Decision:** Lawrence Lundblade will include a curated set (approximately 13 items) of examples in [draft-ietf-cbor-serialization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-serialization/) rather than an exhaustive list of test vectors.
*   **Action Item:** Rohan Mahy to provide additional security considerations for the serialization draft by the end of the week.
*   **Action Item:** Lawrence Lundblade to produce version -05 of [draft-ietf-cbor-serialization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-serialization/) within approximately two weeks, incorporating the examples and addressing Carsten Bormann’s Section 1 PR.
*   **Decision:** The working group will "unpark" [draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-edn-literals/) and [draft-ietf-cbor-packed](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-cbor-packed/) to resume progress.

## Next Steps
*   The Chairs (Barry Leiba and Christian Amsüss) will formalize the plan to unpark the EDN and Packed drafts on the mailing list.
*   Continued discussion on the mailing list regarding the fine points of the serialization framing text.